WEBVTT

00:01.160 --> 00:02.840
You can't live like this another year.

00:02.920 --> 00:06.920
Tommy, you've never even seen Arthur's
kid. Nor John and Esme's.

00:07.000 --> 00:08.920
ADA: <i>I'm staying with Polly.</i>
TOMMY: <i>She's in a bad way.</i>

00:09.000 --> 00:10.080
I'll get through to her.

00:10.160 --> 00:12.880
TOMMY: <i>The union convenor causing all
the trouble. Her name's Jessie Eden.</i>

00:12.960 --> 00:15.080
I will conduct myself as a businessman.

00:15.160 --> 00:16.560
Who says sweetheart.

00:16.640 --> 00:20.400
Today, everyone in the family
received one of these.

00:20.480 --> 00:22.760
TOMMY: <i>Changretta knows where we all
live. We need to be together in a place</i>

00:22.840 --> 00:24.480
<i>even they won't dare to come.</i>

00:24.560 --> 00:25.960
ADA: <i>You mean back home?</i>

00:26.040 --> 00:28.000
MICHAEL: <i>This is the New York Mafia
we're talking about!</i>

00:28.080 --> 00:29.760
JOHN: <i>And we're the Peaky Blinders!</i>

00:29.840 --> 00:32.280
MICHAEL: <i>We're not the Peaky Blinders
unless we're together.</i>

00:32.360 --> 00:34.360
-What's the purpose of your visit?
-Pleasure.

00:42.000 --> 00:43.880
(SIREN WAILING)

01:06.960 --> 01:10.240
<i># I began to warm and chill</i>

01:11.120 --> 01:14.320
<i># To objects and their fields</i>

01:14.760 --> 01:17.960
<i># A ragged cup, a twisted mop</i>

01:18.800 --> 01:21.520
<i># The face of Jesus in my soup</i>

01:22.960 --> 01:26.520
<i># Those sinister dinner deals</i>

01:27.280 --> 01:30.600
<i># The meal trolley's wicked wheels</i>

01:31.000 --> 01:34.520
<i># And the mercy seat is waiting</i>

01:34.840 --> 01:38.560
<i># And I think my head is burning</i>

01:38.640 --> 01:40.800
<i># And in a way I'm yearning</i>

01:40.880 --> 01:46.000
<i># To be done with all this
Weighing of the truth</i>

01:46.360 --> 01:49.920
<i># An eye for an eye
And a tooth for a tooth</i>

01:50.160 --> 01:53.640
<i># And anyway I told the truth</i>

01:53.960 --> 01:57.280
<i># And I'm not afraid to die</i>

01:57.400 --> 02:00.960
<i># And the mercy seat is burning</i>

02:01.040 --> 02:04.680
<i># And I think my head is glowing</i>

02:04.760 --> 02:07.040
<i># And in a way I'm hoping</i>

02:07.240 --> 02:11.960
<i># To be done with all this
Weighing of the truth</i>

02:12.360 --> 02:16.160
<i># An eye for an eye
And a tooth for a tooth</i>

02:16.520 --> 02:19.840
<i># And anyway I told the truth</i>

02:20.280 --> 02:25.280
<i># And I'm afraid I told a lie #</i>

02:27.960 --> 02:31.200
POLLY: Please,
can we get some help here? Please!

02:31.360 --> 02:33.480
It's all right Michael.
It's all right Michael, I'm here.

02:33.560 --> 02:35.720
It's all right Michael,
you're gonna be OK.

02:35.800 --> 02:38.360
Don't leave us now,
just keep keep breathing.

02:38.640 --> 02:40.080
(OVERLAPPING VOICES)

02:41.720 --> 02:46.360
No, no, I don't want fucking
kids in here, I want soldiers.

02:46.440 --> 02:48.880
I don't want fucking kids
who joined just for the sport.

02:49.000 --> 02:49.960
Go on, go.

02:50.040 --> 02:51.720
I want men who've served in here.

02:51.840 --> 02:53.480
-All right, Poll.
-(POLLY SOBBING)

02:54.560 --> 02:56.040
NURSE: Mrs Gray, please.

02:56.120 --> 02:57.960
POLLY: (SOBBING) Don't go, don't go...

02:58.800 --> 03:00.000
DOCTOR: He's in good hands.

03:00.080 --> 03:02.480
TOMMY: Polly? Poll? Poll?

03:02.840 --> 03:05.520
Fuck those bastards responsible!

03:05.600 --> 03:07.040
All right,
let them do their job, all right?

03:07.120 --> 03:09.080
Let them do their job,
I'll get soldiers.

03:09.160 --> 03:11.160
I'll be back. I'll be back.

03:19.800 --> 03:21.160
(DOOR OPENS)

03:37.160 --> 03:38.360
TOMMY: Is it him?

03:40.400 --> 03:41.960
ARTHUR: Yeah.

03:45.680 --> 03:47.560
On his own doorstep.

03:50.040 --> 03:52.240
His own fucking doorstep.

03:58.840 --> 04:01.680
Right, get out. And you, out.

04:09.960 --> 04:12.680
(SCREAMING) What the fuck?

04:16.000 --> 04:17.280
(DOOR CLOSES)

04:21.400 --> 04:22.640
ARTHUR: Poor John.

04:24.720 --> 04:26.280
Fucking gone.

04:27.880 --> 04:29.600
In the bleak midwinter.

04:32.160 --> 04:33.560
We promised, Arthur.

04:33.640 --> 04:35.040
ARTHUR: I can't.

04:36.520 --> 04:38.120
In the hole we promised.

04:39.960 --> 04:43.520
-Can't look at him.
-Come here brother.

04:47.480 --> 04:50.200
Come here. Come on, come here.

04:55.120 --> 04:56.800
ARTHUR: Oh, my!

05:00.920 --> 05:02.320
Now say it.

05:06.480 --> 05:08.000
Say it, brother.

05:13.640 --> 05:15.880
In the bleak midwinter.

05:20.680 --> 05:21.840
(DOOR OPENS)

05:21.960 --> 05:25.120
ESME: You're cursed
and I curse you again!

05:25.200 --> 05:27.320
(SCREAMING)

05:28.440 --> 05:30.640
Come here, come here.

05:32.520 --> 05:33.680
(TOMMY SIGHS)

05:47.280 --> 05:48.960
Leave me with him.

05:49.520 --> 05:53.160
You've spoken to him, now it's my turn.

05:56.640 --> 05:57.800
Arthur?

06:02.040 --> 06:04.960
No peace for either of you, ever.

06:21.000 --> 06:23.040
Our stuff will stay with me.

06:28.720 --> 06:30.600
Taking the children on the road...

06:31.560 --> 06:33.520
to live with decent people.

06:37.320 --> 06:39.600
They'll never know
the curse side of this family.

06:43.360 --> 06:44.960
We're done with them, John.

06:50.480 --> 06:51.920
(FOOTSTEPS RECEDING)

07:02.480 --> 07:04.080
(SIGHS)

07:18.960 --> 07:21.760
-(KNOCK ON DOOR)
-Tommy, they're gathered.

07:22.720 --> 07:24.080
(FOOTSTEPS)

08:12.680 --> 08:13.880
John is dead.

08:17.120 --> 08:19.320
Esme's gone on the road with the Lees.

08:20.240 --> 08:22.000
She's taken the kids.

08:23.640 --> 08:27.560
Michael is badly wounded,
they say it's 60/40 in his favour.

08:27.640 --> 08:30.320
There's no number,
there's no percentages.

08:32.280 --> 08:35.880
So the hand, the hand
beneath him stops him falling.

08:37.120 --> 08:38.680
Spoke to someone...

08:39.840 --> 08:41.080
my son will live.

08:43.600 --> 08:46.040
Michael and John were shot
because we killed someone...

08:48.080 --> 08:49.600
Vincenzo Changretta.

08:49.920 --> 08:52.080
His son Luca
has come to take revenge.

08:53.240 --> 08:55.960
Men from New York
and Sicily are in Birmingham.

08:56.680 --> 08:59.920
These men will not leave our city
until the whole family is dead.

09:00.480 --> 09:02.560
That's how it works, an eye for an eye.

09:03.920 --> 09:06.520
-It's called vendetta.
-ARTHUR: Yeah, well...

09:08.880 --> 09:10.520
The bullet's been written...

09:12.320 --> 09:14.040
It says Luca.

09:15.640 --> 09:17.160
When the time comes...

09:18.880 --> 09:20.400
and it will come...

09:22.200 --> 09:24.000
me as the oldest brother...

09:25.880 --> 09:29.760
will put this bullet
into his fucking head.

09:37.040 --> 09:38.680
There's been some bad blood between us.

09:42.640 --> 09:43.720
(POLLY SCOFFING)

09:43.800 --> 09:45.120
ARTHUR: Polly, please?

09:48.200 --> 09:51.600
Until this business is settled
we stay together.

09:52.520 --> 09:53.840
We stay here...

09:54.800 --> 09:58.280
Small Heath, Bordesley,
Hay Mills down to Greet.

09:58.400 --> 10:00.360
We know every face,

10:00.440 --> 10:02.280
every man is a soldier in this army.

10:03.920 --> 10:06.280
These men are professionals
and they're good at what they do,

10:06.400 --> 10:08.960
so we're gonna need more than we have.

10:09.040 --> 10:11.320
We send a message to Aberama Gold.

10:12.200 --> 10:14.840
No. No, Tom.

10:15.320 --> 10:18.800
I'll get you 50 Lee boys. Good men, Tom.

10:18.880 --> 10:20.960
I don't need good men Johnny,
for this I need bad men.

10:21.040 --> 10:23.520
Tommy, his people
are fucking savages.

10:23.600 --> 10:25.480
You know, heathens, Tom.

10:25.560 --> 10:27.480
They don't even let them in the fair,

10:27.560 --> 10:30.920
so they come and steal our horses.
You know, stealing from their own, Tom.

10:31.400 --> 10:33.840
So this is the plan, Thomas?

10:35.080 --> 10:36.600
This is the plan?

10:37.480 --> 10:41.880
Bullet with a name on it,
help from a bunch of savages.

10:44.000 --> 10:45.600
We're gonna go on the offensive.

10:46.080 --> 10:48.920
-I've spoken to Moss.
-(SCOFFS) Moss?

10:49.040 --> 10:50.520
I've spoken to Moss.

10:51.920 --> 10:57.040
Moss is putting out word.
Eyes and ears so we can find them.

10:59.600 --> 11:02.280
Yeah, the truth is, the police
are busy with the revolution.

11:03.000 --> 11:05.280
Moss says they're
expecting strikes and riots

11:05.400 --> 11:07.120
when the weather gets warm
and the Bolsheviks plan to...

11:07.200 --> 11:09.160
The Bolsheviks
couldn't plan a fucking picnic.

11:09.280 --> 11:11.040
-He's reading the wrong papers.
-Ada!

11:12.400 --> 11:16.560
Real, or not real, the coppers
don't give a fuck about us, all right?

11:19.840 --> 11:21.440
Which means...

11:22.560 --> 11:24.360
that here today in this room...

11:25.680 --> 11:28.080
we have to agree to
end this war between us.

11:32.480 --> 11:33.600
Take a vote.

11:36.760 --> 11:38.000
Peace.

11:39.400 --> 11:41.640
I was never a part of this, but...

11:41.720 --> 11:42.960
peace.

11:43.600 --> 11:44.960
Peace.

11:46.080 --> 11:47.640
Peace.

11:48.520 --> 11:49.920
Peace.

11:50.000 --> 11:51.640
Shut up, Finn.

11:51.720 --> 11:52.800
Why can't I say peace?

11:53.280 --> 11:55.640
Arthur, let him have his say.

11:56.200 --> 11:58.640
Finn? Sit at the table.

12:03.400 --> 12:04.480
Little bastard...

12:06.960 --> 12:09.080
Sending a fucking kid,
Sergeant Major...

12:10.360 --> 12:11.600
to do men's work.

12:15.160 --> 12:17.440
My son's not here to speak...

12:23.400 --> 12:25.720
So I'll speak on behalf of us both.

12:31.480 --> 12:32.960
Truce.

12:38.600 --> 12:39.920
Five for peace.

12:40.560 --> 12:42.440
Two for truce, one abstension.

12:43.160 --> 12:45.480
Let's get on with the war.

12:47.800 --> 12:49.640
(HORSE WHINNIES)

12:50.160 --> 12:51.800
(CHATTER)

12:56.000 --> 12:59.040
Whoa. Curly, how are ya?

12:59.120 --> 13:01.080
Here, catch.

13:04.720 --> 13:08.640
Right, come on then,
boys, unload, unload.

13:41.840 --> 13:43.760
Hat.

13:46.880 --> 13:48.240
Blues and Villa goalkeeper?

13:49.080 --> 13:51.360
Dan Tremelling
plays in goal for the Blues

13:51.440 --> 13:53.000
and Tommy Jackson for the Villa.

13:54.240 --> 13:55.400
Fair enough.

14:03.600 --> 14:05.360
-Charlie?
-What is it, Curly?

14:05.600 --> 14:07.040
We've run out of bullets Charlie.

14:08.520 --> 14:10.040
We need more ammunition.

14:10.640 --> 14:12.080
More ammunition.

14:12.480 --> 14:14.400
Johnny, more ammo.

14:15.360 --> 14:16.840
(IN ROMANI)

14:27.280 --> 14:29.400
We're like sitting ducks
here if the wops come.

14:29.840 --> 14:32.680
Yeah, well, Tommy said
we should do it in the open.

14:48.160 --> 14:50.040
This is how John wanted to go.

14:51.480 --> 14:52.680
On the smoke.

14:53.440 --> 14:54.760
And the truth is...

14:55.680 --> 14:59.120
we died together once before.

15:00.320 --> 15:01.400
Arthur,

15:02.240 --> 15:03.400
me,

15:04.800 --> 15:06.080
Danny Whizzbang,

15:07.360 --> 15:08.600
Freddie Thorne,

15:09.520 --> 15:10.680
Jeremiah,

15:11.440 --> 15:12.640
and John.

15:14.760 --> 15:16.440
We were cut off from the retreat...

15:17.720 --> 15:21.400
No bullets left, waiting for
the Prussian cavalry

15:21.480 --> 15:23.240
to come and to finish us off.

15:25.720 --> 15:27.280
And while we waited...

15:29.280 --> 15:33.120
Jeremiah said, "We should sing,
'In the Bleak Midwinter.'"

15:36.040 --> 15:37.360
But we were spared.

15:38.600 --> 15:39.920
The enemy never came.

15:40.680 --> 15:42.080
And we all agreed...

15:45.160 --> 15:48.120
that everything after that was extra.

15:49.760 --> 15:51.280
And when our time came...

15:52.200 --> 15:53.440
we'd all remember.

15:53.520 --> 15:55.560
POLLY: You remember that God spared you.

15:57.000 --> 15:59.720
But what did you do with that
extra time that he gave you, eh, Thomas?

16:11.840 --> 16:13.280
(SPEAKING ITALIAN)

17:27.440 --> 17:28.680
(SHOUTING)

17:29.560 --> 17:31.960
At ease! At ease.

17:32.080 --> 17:33.920
Do not return fire.

17:34.000 --> 17:38.560
I repeat, do not return fire.
Stand down.

17:39.120 --> 17:41.960
The men doing the firing
are on our side.

18:02.840 --> 18:04.160
I took the trouble...

18:04.920 --> 18:08.640
of giving an invitation
to Aberama Gold.

18:09.560 --> 18:12.280
Oh fuck! Now it's begun.

18:17.680 --> 18:19.880
Put it out in the open on purpose.

18:21.680 --> 18:24.440
You used John's funeral fire
as a fucking beacon.

18:25.400 --> 18:26.880
ARTHUR: We were never
in any danger Polly.

18:26.960 --> 18:28.040
You set a trap.

18:28.320 --> 18:32.560
Finn? Finn? Go to
the yard and light the fires.

18:32.680 --> 18:35.440
You set a trap with us as fucking bait.

18:37.440 --> 18:38.600
Who's dead?

18:40.000 --> 18:41.360
TOMMY: Our enemies.

18:45.360 --> 18:48.440
-Who's dead?
-You wanna know, Poll?

18:48.960 --> 18:51.560
Two fucking no good Italians
heard about the vendetta,

18:51.680 --> 18:54.120
tried to make a fucking name
for themselves, that's who.

18:54.280 --> 18:57.080
We got word to them about the funeral,

18:57.160 --> 18:58.440
the where, the when...

18:59.080 --> 19:01.040
Told them where to
stand for the best shot.

19:02.400 --> 19:04.760
TOMMY: And Aberama Gold
would do the rest.

19:05.640 --> 19:07.400
That's the language of vendetta,

19:07.480 --> 19:10.440
they take one of ours,
we take two of theirs.

19:11.720 --> 19:15.160
You used your own brother's funeral.

19:19.880 --> 19:22.320
When did we vote on this, Tommy?

19:25.000 --> 19:29.080
Curly, get a boat ready
to take the bodies to the city.

19:29.160 --> 19:31.680
And another boat for anyone,

19:31.760 --> 19:34.400
anyone who wants no more part of this.

19:34.520 --> 19:36.120
'Cause this is how it's gonna be.

19:37.560 --> 19:39.320
Polly?

19:40.880 --> 19:44.200
I'm not staying for
this, Arthur, I'm going home.

19:44.640 --> 19:47.880
Oh, yeah? Home's 57, Watery Lane.

19:48.600 --> 19:53.200
You go there, lock
the doors, you wait for me.

20:06.280 --> 20:07.320
Key to number 57.

20:07.400 --> 20:08.560
I'm going home to the country.

20:08.640 --> 20:11.440
You will stay here until it's over.
Take the fucking key, Linda.

20:11.920 --> 20:14.440
Look, away from here
you are a weakness to all of us.

20:14.520 --> 20:17.160
They will take you hostage and the baby,

20:17.240 --> 20:19.040
they will use the baby.

20:20.120 --> 20:25.040
Take it. Put the kettle on,
wait for your husband.

20:31.440 --> 20:33.720
The only way any of you
Shelbys will leave this place

20:33.840 --> 20:35.920
is on a cloud of smoke like John.

20:36.440 --> 20:38.680
Well, you're a Shelby now too, Linda.

20:43.240 --> 20:45.120
Five hundred each.
A thousand for the brace.

20:46.000 --> 20:47.400
Where do you want them?

20:47.480 --> 20:49.560
Charlie, take him to the yard.

21:23.120 --> 21:25.000
TOMMY: Not too far
and not too deep, Curly,

21:25.080 --> 21:26.520
I need the message to get through.

21:26.600 --> 21:27.920
Okay, Tommy.

21:28.400 --> 21:30.840
Finn, you go with him.

21:32.320 --> 21:34.560
Go on. Go with him.

21:36.360 --> 21:39.280
Oh, Tom, uh, tell Janet to
save me some goose, please.

21:58.560 --> 22:00.640
On your feet.

22:15.840 --> 22:17.240
Wait outside.

22:28.640 --> 22:30.040
Hello, Mum.

22:34.200 --> 22:36.040
POLLY: They said you'd be out cold.

22:39.760 --> 22:41.800
-No, don't move.
-(SIGHS)

22:42.600 --> 22:44.560
The doctor said they've
sewn you up like a football.

22:45.040 --> 22:46.320
What else did he say?

22:47.960 --> 22:49.440
He said you took four bullets.

22:50.760 --> 22:54.160
Only one was live, one was ricochet...

22:56.880 --> 22:58.240
Two were already spent.

23:01.680 --> 23:03.480
Two had passed through John.

23:06.480 --> 23:09.160
Last thing I remember
was his face.

23:13.720 --> 23:15.360
I watched him go.

23:21.800 --> 23:23.760
Where's Tommy?

23:23.840 --> 23:25.920
Oh, don't worry about Tommy,
just get better.

23:26.000 --> 23:27.480
Where is he?

23:29.400 --> 23:31.520
Tommy's back.

23:31.600 --> 23:35.760
We're all back. Garrison,
Watery Lane, Charlie's...

23:41.120 --> 23:43.280
-I need a cigarette.
-No.

23:46.920 --> 23:47.840
I made a decision.

23:47.920 --> 23:49.600
Give me a cigarette, Mum.

23:49.760 --> 23:52.320
-It's not allowed.
-It's not allowed?

24:04.400 --> 24:07.360
-I've decided we're gonna get away.
-Mm, yeah?

24:08.400 --> 24:11.080
Just me and you, Australia.

24:12.920 --> 24:15.440
I've been to the Cunard office
and I've got a magazine.

24:16.000 --> 24:18.480
-Hmm.
-Now, America's no good

24:18.560 --> 24:21.200
because that's where they are,
but there's no Italians in Australia.

24:21.280 --> 24:22.960
I think there are, Mum.

24:23.920 --> 24:25.240
Bad ones, I mean.

24:26.160 --> 24:27.800
Have you stopped taking
those prison tablets?

24:27.880 --> 24:29.280
Don't you worry about me.

24:29.360 --> 24:30.600
Well, I do.

24:31.040 --> 24:32.920
And just you get better.

24:33.680 --> 24:36.920
The doctor says it'll be five weeks,
then you'll be up and walking.

24:37.680 --> 24:40.960
Now, there's a boat that
leaves on February the 13th.

24:41.040 --> 24:42.880
Tell Tommy I need to see him.

24:43.680 --> 24:46.520
Tell him to bring a gun small enough
to fit in the chamber pot, in case...

24:46.600 --> 24:48.840
I've banned Tommy from coming.

24:51.560 --> 24:53.080
The factory's coming
back to work tomorrow.

24:53.160 --> 24:54.560
Just forget about the fucking factories.

24:54.640 --> 24:56.200
Is there any word of
them going out on strike?

24:56.280 --> 24:57.520
We can go to Australia,

24:58.520 --> 25:00.880
it'll just be you, me, and your sister,

25:01.000 --> 25:04.000
'cause I've found out where she was
buried, somewhere outside Melbourne.

25:04.120 --> 25:05.360
Listen, Mum...

25:09.280 --> 25:11.280
I'm gonna get better slowly.

25:12.400 --> 25:14.200
But you need to get better fast.

25:15.960 --> 25:18.600
Without you he falls apart
and without him...

25:21.600 --> 25:23.440
without him, they'll take us all.

25:25.200 --> 25:27.320
You've got to get us through this.

25:30.240 --> 25:31.760
And I promise...

25:32.600 --> 25:35.280
I'll board that train with
you and we'll go to Australia.

26:10.600 --> 26:14.600
I like your yard, Mr Strong.
How much would you take for it?

26:16.880 --> 26:18.320
It's not for sale.

26:18.720 --> 26:20.000
Not for sale?

26:20.760 --> 26:22.040
Okay.

26:34.120 --> 26:38.160
I just took a look around.
I like this place.

26:39.960 --> 26:43.360
Fire for melting silver,
canal to get it away.

26:44.440 --> 26:45.560
How much?

26:49.480 --> 26:51.600
Nothing you see here
is for sale, Mr Gold.

26:51.720 --> 26:54.280
Oh, everything's for sale, everything.

26:59.800 --> 27:03.440
You tell Mr Strong
I'm going to buy his yard.

27:05.120 --> 27:07.360
This yard has been in
his family since they settled.

27:07.480 --> 27:09.840
But I've decided to
make it part of our deal.

27:16.520 --> 27:17.800
Charlie?

27:20.320 --> 27:21.640
Charlie, come here.

27:26.840 --> 27:28.720
I'm gonna spin a coin
for your yard, Charlie.

27:29.880 --> 27:31.080
You're going to what?

27:31.600 --> 27:32.960
If it's heads...

27:33.760 --> 27:37.000
Abbie here takes all
of this with my blessing.

27:37.560 --> 27:38.680
Tommy?

27:39.920 --> 27:41.400
And if it's tails...

27:44.040 --> 27:45.840
I fuck your daughter, Mr Gold.

27:50.680 --> 27:52.400
You have three daughters I hear,

27:52.960 --> 27:56.560
and Esmeralda is the oldest
and also the prettiest,

27:56.680 --> 27:58.360
so I'll have her.

27:58.440 --> 28:01.320
So make her part of the deal
and spin against the yard.

28:02.040 --> 28:03.880
Tommy, for fuck's sake.

28:04.320 --> 28:07.720
Here, you toss the coin, Mr Gold.

28:21.680 --> 28:22.880
No.

28:24.880 --> 28:27.040
Please don't believe this is a joke,

28:27.160 --> 28:30.040
the coin to us is sacred, yes, Arthur?

28:30.120 --> 28:31.400
Sacred.

28:35.240 --> 28:38.440
You toss that coin, you take
a bet before witnesses,

28:38.840 --> 28:40.200
and if I win...

28:41.240 --> 28:42.640
Then we'll insist

28:43.400 --> 28:49.640
that the terms of this agreement...
wager are fulfilled.

28:54.080 --> 28:55.360
Toss the coin, Mr Gold.

29:12.960 --> 29:16.240
Tommy Shelby, OBE...

29:20.560 --> 29:22.240
No wager today...

29:23.240 --> 29:26.600
but with this penny I will buy
a flower to put on your grave...

29:29.400 --> 29:30.880
When the time comes.

29:33.560 --> 29:35.040
And before that time...

29:36.360 --> 29:41.280
please don't again disrespect
my friends or their valued property.

29:43.600 --> 29:46.200
We missed Christmas, let's have it now.

29:47.920 --> 29:50.160
Peace on earth, goodwill to all men.

29:53.600 --> 29:54.880
Drink?

30:00.360 --> 30:01.920
Rum, Curly?

30:02.520 --> 30:05.800
Toast to my brother, John,
raise your glasses all of you.

30:05.880 --> 30:08.840
Raise them up, all of you.

30:09.520 --> 30:10.760
John Shelby.

30:11.880 --> 30:15.120
I've got wire, I've got chains,
I've got the steel rods. Now what?

30:15.240 --> 30:17.760
Right, put the steel rods
up the geese's arse there,

30:17.880 --> 30:20.080
and then you put those
steel rods above the fire,

30:20.160 --> 30:22.360
spinning the rod to stop
the bird from burning.

30:22.840 --> 30:24.400
ALL: Cheers!

30:24.800 --> 30:26.120
JOHNNY: You did get potatoes, Charlie?

30:26.200 --> 30:28.400
No, I didn't get fucking potatoes,
what's the matter with you?

30:28.560 --> 30:31.520
I don't want that bastard Aberama Gold

30:31.600 --> 30:33.960
putting it around that we live
like Diddycoys.

30:34.040 --> 30:38.360
I want him to see that we live proper,
that we eat proper, in the proper way.

30:38.440 --> 30:40.480
What the fuck are you talking about?

30:40.560 --> 30:42.480
I'll get the potatoes me self.

30:49.760 --> 30:52.320
Never thought my high
fucking heels from Paris

30:52.400 --> 30:56.240
would be stepping through the horse shit
of Small Heath ever again.

30:56.360 --> 30:58.000
Temporary, Polly.

30:58.080 --> 31:00.400
LIZZIE: Yeah, until hell freezes over.

31:40.160 --> 31:41.760
(CLEARS THROAT) How's Michael?

31:42.320 --> 31:46.080
You said eight men from New York,
seven from Sicily, at £500 each?

31:47.040 --> 31:48.640
Course you can afford it.

31:49.120 --> 31:50.600
Most we'll do ourselves.

31:51.800 --> 31:54.160
How many of your factories
are in the safe territories?

31:54.240 --> 31:55.440
Seventy percent.

31:56.360 --> 31:59.040
Shelby Company Limited
will continue to manufacture.

32:01.480 --> 32:03.800
Lizzie says its only whores these days?

32:05.000 --> 32:06.120
Yeah.

32:08.520 --> 32:10.520
Have them smuggled in, I suppose.

32:14.040 --> 32:15.400
I need you back, Polly.

32:15.520 --> 32:17.560
Paying whores for sex.

32:17.640 --> 32:19.240
Paying killers to kill.

32:19.320 --> 32:20.520
Yep, nothing for nothing.

32:20.640 --> 32:21.960
Poor Thomas.

32:25.400 --> 32:26.880
You know, our mother went this way.

32:27.000 --> 32:31.200
Spirits and ghosts, tablets,
fucking... fucking séances,

32:31.280 --> 32:33.240
scaring us kids
halfway to fuckin' death.

32:33.320 --> 32:36.280
Yeah, well. I'm not going that way.

32:38.160 --> 32:40.440
'Cause in the smoke
I realised something.

32:43.440 --> 32:44.960
I'm just like you now.

32:45.840 --> 32:47.360
You and Arthur.

32:49.640 --> 32:53.520
I was dead in that noose
and then I was saved,

32:53.640 --> 32:55.600
so everything from now on is extra.

32:56.120 --> 32:58.480
But what I didn't understand until today

32:59.400 --> 33:01.320
is when you're dead already...

33:03.600 --> 33:05.000
you're free.

33:09.240 --> 33:10.880
Fucking love it.

33:14.120 --> 33:16.640
I'll help you because
Michael wants me to help you.

33:18.800 --> 33:20.280
Starting now...

33:21.360 --> 33:25.720
Get your whores vetted by Lizzie,
they'll use your weakness.

33:25.840 --> 33:27.560
Don't take any new men on
in the factories

33:27.640 --> 33:29.640
unless you know their families.

33:32.440 --> 33:37.320
And your new friend,
Mr Aberama Gold...

33:38.400 --> 33:41.200
he wants something
other than just money.

33:41.840 --> 33:45.680
I see things in the air around people,
but it's not just the tablets.

33:48.200 --> 33:49.560
It's real.

33:50.640 --> 33:53.000
Ask him what he really wants.

34:32.880 --> 34:35.160
She's a fine beast this one.

34:37.520 --> 34:39.920
Nothing you see is for sale, Mr Shelby.

34:45.560 --> 34:48.160
You know your grandfather
camped with mine for a while?

34:48.920 --> 34:50.160
Yep...

34:50.760 --> 34:51.880
And didn't last.

34:51.960 --> 34:56.120
No, it ended badly
in a pub called the Wenlock.

34:57.160 --> 34:59.760
We were owed money, still are.

35:07.800 --> 35:12.400
Other than money, and this
scrapyard that's clearly not for sale,

35:14.400 --> 35:16.040
what is it that you
want from me, Mr Gold?

35:18.160 --> 35:20.080
How do you know
I want anything from you?

35:21.520 --> 35:25.400
Well, because my company treasurer

35:25.480 --> 35:29.160
is a certified accountant
and also apparently, a witch.

35:31.680 --> 35:33.360
You're a sporting man.

35:35.600 --> 35:38.040
-Yes, I am.
-And a gambling man.

35:41.760 --> 35:43.920
Bonnie, take off your shirt.

35:48.480 --> 35:52.920
What I want from you, Mr Shelby,
is for you to take a gamble on him.

35:53.240 --> 35:56.240
I want you to help
my son achieve his ambition.

35:59.360 --> 36:01.760
(GRUNTING)

36:03.760 --> 36:05.840
What ambition might that be?

36:37.440 --> 36:38.960
(KNOCKING <i>AT</i> DOOR)

36:46.520 --> 36:48.280
(KNOCKING)

36:50.560 --> 36:51.640
Who is it?

36:51.960 --> 36:54.040
Inspector Moss.

37:01.920 --> 37:04.480
-I'm looking for Tommy.
-He's at Charlie's.

37:05.120 --> 37:07.880
But I wouldn't go there,
some bad men have arrived.

37:08.520 --> 37:09.720
Yes, I've heard.

37:09.840 --> 37:12.960
They'll be drunk by now, or worse.

37:13.960 --> 37:15.480
Can you take a message?

37:16.560 --> 37:18.760
The, uh, intelligence service in London

37:18.840 --> 37:21.160
have sent seven officers up
to Birmingham

37:21.320 --> 37:24.760
to check out the investigation
into communists and seditionists.

37:24.840 --> 37:28.040
They've got a list of people
of great interest and, uh,

37:28.120 --> 37:31.640
top of that list is
Ada Thorne, formerly Shelby.

37:31.720 --> 37:35.200
Now, they seem to think that
she came back from New York

37:35.280 --> 37:37.840
to organise a revolution in Birmingham.

37:38.000 --> 37:39.480
Well, tell them they're wrong.

37:40.000 --> 37:42.760
Ada Shelby's now firmly back
in place in the family business.

37:42.840 --> 37:45.760
Thing is, when you get
a mark against your name...

37:46.400 --> 37:48.600
it's very hard to shift it.

37:49.480 --> 37:50.920
They will come looking for her.

37:51.000 --> 37:54.640
Well, tell them there's a queue.
Everybody wants a Shelby.

37:55.880 --> 37:57.320
Mrs Shelby...

37:58.480 --> 38:03.200
These are military men,
no less dangerous than any Italians.

38:04.160 --> 38:07.680
You tell Tommy,
I think he'll understand.

38:09.680 --> 38:11.320
Say goodnight to you then.

38:47.320 --> 38:49.920
-Hello, Curly.
-Oh, hello.

38:50.000 --> 38:53.440
I'm here to collect Mr Shelby's
horse. I'm a little early, I think.

38:53.560 --> 38:56.560
Are you going
to train the horse to race?

38:56.680 --> 38:57.760
Yes.

38:58.240 --> 39:00.480
Don't use a crop, she's very gentle.

39:01.320 --> 39:03.040
-I won't.
-CHARLIE: Yo.

39:03.120 --> 39:04.360
I, I...

39:08.040 --> 39:09.880
MAY: How is Mr Shelby?

39:10.360 --> 39:13.840
CURLY: Well, now he's got the Americans
after him, he's a bit hard on people.

39:14.160 --> 39:16.560
-The Americans?
-Yeah, they call them the Mafia.

39:17.880 --> 39:18.960
Dear God.

39:19.080 --> 39:22.200
Yeah, there's 15 of them.
Yeah, they want to kill us all,

39:22.280 --> 39:24.480
but we got guns and grenades
and, and Polly's back,

39:24.560 --> 39:26.480
so it's gonna be okay, yeah.

39:27.320 --> 39:28.760
I'll get the horse.

39:49.680 --> 39:52.080
Mr Shelby, thank God you're back,
we've got real trouble.

39:52.600 --> 39:53.920
TOMMY: What meetings do I have today?

39:54.000 --> 39:57.480
Um, well, uh, there's a supplier
from Coventry at 10:00,

39:57.560 --> 39:59.840
uh, the convener with
the boiler makers unit at 11 :00,

39:59.960 --> 40:01.440
and then Chamber of Commerce at 1 :00.

40:01.560 --> 40:02.640
But that isn't the thing...

40:02.720 --> 40:05.040
Right. Clear a space here,
move this car back,

40:05.160 --> 40:07.320
give me a hundred feet of rope
and a bell.

40:07.400 --> 40:09.240
-Rope?
-Yep, and a bell.

40:09.800 --> 40:11.840
Mr Shelby, this place
is about to explode.

40:12.000 --> 40:13.600
A rope and a bell, Devlin.

40:13.720 --> 40:15.080
Bonnie, this way.

40:15.240 --> 40:16.520
Yes, Mr Shelby.

40:17.640 --> 40:21.280
And by the way, the revolution
is scheduled to begin at noon.

40:23.520 --> 40:26.160
TOMMY: There he is, Billy Mills,

40:26.240 --> 40:28.240
former heavyweight champion,

40:28.320 --> 40:30.280
Staffordshire, Warwickshire
and Worcestershire.

40:30.400 --> 40:31.440
Hello, Billy.

40:31.760 --> 40:32.640
Yeah.

40:33.120 --> 40:35.520
And now I work for you, Mr Shelby,

40:35.640 --> 40:37.240
for not enough money.

40:38.640 --> 40:41.400
Right. That enough for you?

40:43.240 --> 40:44.440
Enough for what?

40:44.520 --> 40:48.200
Someone here who wants to fight you.
Bonnie Gold, come here, son.

40:49.720 --> 40:51.320
I'm a heavyweight,

40:51.440 --> 40:52.960
he's a welterweight at best.

40:53.080 --> 40:54.960
Nevertheless, he wants to fight you.

40:56.720 --> 41:00.520
Yeah. And then when I damage him,
the Blinders will take my eyes.

41:01.160 --> 41:04.560
No comeback, Billy,
just a fight, Queens bury Rules.

41:05.560 --> 41:07.360
BILLY: When?
TOMMY: Now.

41:07.440 --> 41:08.760
BILLY: Where?
TOMMY: Here!

41:08.840 --> 41:11.440
ARTHUR: Right, you lot, come here.

41:11.520 --> 41:15.080
Let's make it interesting.
Come place a wager with me.

41:15.160 --> 41:16.800
I'll give you good odds.

41:16.880 --> 41:20.520
I'll give you good odds on the boy,
even better on the big lad.

41:20.720 --> 41:22.640
There you go, what you want?

41:25.480 --> 41:27.400
Bonnie, come here, son.

41:34.120 --> 41:35.760
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

41:38.960 --> 41:41.600
-Give him one!
-Let's have it then!

42:10.680 --> 42:13.200
Your boy knows he can hit back, right?

42:13.920 --> 42:16.440
Told him in the professional game
people want their money's worth,

42:16.520 --> 42:18.000
don't win too fast.

42:22.280 --> 42:23.760
But if you've seen enough...

42:26.480 --> 42:28.120
Finish it, Bonnie.

42:34.640 --> 42:37.560
Fuck me. That was a punch.

42:38.240 --> 42:40.240
What's he got, horseshoes
in those gloves or what?

42:40.400 --> 42:43.840
No, just his dad's strength
and his mother's temper.

42:48.920 --> 42:51.320
TOMMY: Does he have fits?
ABARAMAH: No.

42:51.440 --> 42:53.080
-Asthma?
-No.

42:53.160 --> 42:54.360
How's he cut?

42:54.440 --> 42:56.640
Well, no one's cut him
yet, but his skin's thick.

42:56.920 --> 42:59.840
-Does he drink?
-Water, sometimes.

42:59.920 --> 43:02.160
-How many fights?
-Twenty-five, bare knuckle,

43:02.240 --> 43:05.560
all knockouts, five with gloves
in pastures, all knockouts.

43:05.640 --> 43:07.560
Against Romany fighters?

43:07.640 --> 43:09.640
That's why they won't let us in the
fairs no more, he keeps winning.

43:09.720 --> 43:12.120
I could fight a fucking tree
and knock it out, Mr Shelby.

43:12.200 --> 43:14.560
(LAUGHS) I like him. I like it.

43:14.680 --> 43:18.240
-Mrs Eden is waiting upstairs
-I'll be there in a minute. Arthur?

43:33.920 --> 43:35.400
Mr Shelby's on his way.

43:35.480 --> 43:36.960
Fight in the workshop?

43:37.160 --> 43:39.920
No, no, just a bit of sport.

43:40.000 --> 43:41.000
Do you want some more tea?

43:41.120 --> 43:42.560
No, what kind of sport?

43:44.320 --> 43:46.720
Sport between men, Mrs Eden.

43:48.120 --> 43:49.720
Actually, I'm Miss Eden.

43:51.600 --> 43:54.280
Be patient, a good man will come.

43:55.280 --> 43:58.200
TOMMY: What do you think?
ARTHUR: No, that was over fast.

43:58.280 --> 44:00.000
Yeah, but you can tell, eh?

44:00.080 --> 44:02.560
I'd give him to the Irish boys
at Digbeth, they can teach him.

44:02.720 --> 44:05.400
-And then what?
-We promote him.

44:05.760 --> 44:08.560
Big money in London,
New York, if he's good.

44:08.680 --> 44:10.120
We control him.

44:10.200 --> 44:13.040
On the book, control the odds,
like a horse.

44:13.160 --> 44:17.280
Control when he wins, when he loses.
Alfie Solomon runs a fighter,

44:17.360 --> 44:21.040
says it's fuckin' money for nothing,
fighting's been good for us,

44:21.120 --> 44:22.640
better if you know who's gonna win.

44:24.320 --> 44:26.680
But we got a lot going on, that's all.

44:26.800 --> 44:30.120
Yeah. That's why it'd be good
to have the kid around.

44:31.120 --> 44:32.600
We take the fucking kid on,

44:33.320 --> 44:35.880
one day he may end up
fucking taking a bullet for you.

44:36.360 --> 44:38.400
Can't afford to lose
another brother, can I?

44:40.400 --> 44:43.680
No one else is like him,
so he's all right.

44:44.360 --> 44:45.560
Come on.

44:49.640 --> 44:51.400
All right, I'll do it.

44:51.880 --> 44:54.280
ABARAMAH: But we need to
do a deal about money.

44:54.360 --> 44:56.800
-ARTHUR: Hmm.
-Yeah. Speak to my accountant.

44:56.920 --> 44:58.280
-The witch?
-Yeah.

44:58.360 --> 45:00.840
So when will my first real
fight be do you think, Mr Shelby?

45:00.960 --> 45:04.200
Soon as we can find anyone stupid
enough to get in the ring with you.

45:05.360 --> 45:06.600
God help him.

45:07.680 --> 45:09.120
There you go, Bonnie.

45:11.920 --> 45:13.640
You're a Peaky Blinder now, son.

45:22.720 --> 45:27.520
-There you go, the lion's share.
-Thank you.

45:40.320 --> 45:44.240
Mr Shelby...
I understand you've had a bereavement.

45:46.240 --> 45:48.240
TOMMY: I'm here to talk business.

45:49.440 --> 45:50.840
Then I'll be blunt.

45:51.800 --> 45:52.800
As will I.

45:52.920 --> 45:54.680
What you're doing here is robbery.

45:54.760 --> 45:56.240
Every man is free to leave.

45:56.320 --> 45:59.720
You cut five shillings
from the weekly wage.

46:02.000 --> 46:04.840
And you said, if I did that

46:04.960 --> 46:08.240
you'd bring every man and woman
in all my factories out on strike.

46:08.920 --> 46:10.120
Yes.

46:12.600 --> 46:14.800
Do you have a whistle?

46:16.080 --> 46:18.440
If so, blow it.

46:24.000 --> 46:26.400
I thought at least
we might have a discussion,

46:27.280 --> 46:29.000
as I do with other owners.

46:29.680 --> 46:31.360
I'm not other owners.

46:31.920 --> 46:32.960
No.

46:34.440 --> 46:37.960
You believe because coal is expensive
and it's been a cold winter

46:38.040 --> 46:40.240
and because wages have been
cut over the past twelve months,

46:40.320 --> 46:45.000
you think because of all that
nobody will walk out on strike,

46:46.080 --> 46:47.640
because no one can afford to.

46:49.280 --> 46:51.480
And until recently
that would've been true.

46:52.960 --> 46:55.040
But something has changed
this past year.

46:56.520 --> 47:01.800
Cold winter in the east,
people are not afraid anymore.

47:04.520 --> 47:06.480
I have it on very good authority

47:06.560 --> 47:09.520
that the Bolsheviks couldn't
organise a fucking picnic.

47:12.920 --> 47:14.640
You know, Mr Shelby...

47:16.160 --> 47:18.360
It's almost as if you want trouble.

47:25.560 --> 47:28.040
If the rule of law
in Birmingham were to break down

47:28.120 --> 47:32.680
during this period
of turmoil for my family,

47:32.760 --> 47:36.480
then yes, that would
indeed have its benefits

47:37.320 --> 47:40.280
for reasons you could not understand.

47:40.360 --> 47:41.720
I've heard rumours.

47:42.840 --> 47:44.520
Sport between men.

47:44.840 --> 47:47.480
Just blow your fucking whistle, eh?

47:57.840 --> 48:01.240
(DOOR OPENS AND CLOSES)

48:06.400 --> 48:07.920
(WHISTLE BLOWING)

48:10.680 --> 48:12.760
MAN: Tools down, we've had a clearing!

48:14.080 --> 48:16.520
Right, come on you lot,
put your tools down!

48:16.680 --> 48:18.880
(CHATTER)

48:29.320 --> 48:30.880
MAN: Everyone out!

48:33.520 --> 48:35.200
I said, everyone out.

48:36.760 --> 48:38.760
Stop working immediately.

48:53.400 --> 48:54.440
TOMMY: Yeah, come in.

49:03.360 --> 49:04.800
I did say this would happen.

49:07.080 --> 49:08.600
Who's next?

49:08.680 --> 49:14.360
Um, he's a, a delegate from
the European Council for Trade.

49:15.720 --> 49:18.640
He's here to talk about
the import of car parts to France.

49:18.760 --> 49:21.200
-Right.
-He's come all the way from Paris,

49:22.080 --> 49:25.440
but given the circumstances
I could send him away?

49:28.800 --> 49:31.000
Given what circumstances? Send him in.

49:50.640 --> 49:56.280
Mr Shelby, this is
Monsieur Paz from Paris.

50:02.960 --> 50:04.520
I heard you had trouble.

50:06.720 --> 50:08.040
It's good of you to see me.

50:10.360 --> 50:12.080
You just came from Paris, eh?

50:17.800 --> 50:19.280
You know Paris?

50:20.800 --> 50:22.760
I left Paris in a cattle truck.

50:27.360 --> 50:28.960
They said you were French.

50:31.080 --> 50:33.720
Well, I came here from Paris.

50:35.040 --> 50:37.040
That does not mean I'm French.

50:43.280 --> 50:44.840
Guess where I'm from.

50:50.000 --> 50:52.840
Well, in my cattle truck in Paris...

50:55.240 --> 51:00.480
There were American
soldiers who played cards.

51:06.440 --> 51:07.960
They sound like you.

51:08.640 --> 51:11.880
Yeah. Did you win?

51:14.280 --> 51:17.840
You didn't come on a train. Your suit
is pressed, your shoes are clean.

51:18.760 --> 51:21.080
Where do you get your suits made?

51:21.880 --> 51:25.640
I have a tailor in New York City.

51:27.480 --> 51:28.600
Look.

51:32.080 --> 51:35.360
Funacci, Italian.

51:36.400 --> 51:38.040
He's my uncle.

51:38.120 --> 51:40.520
He makes suits in
the basement of Madge Street.

51:42.240 --> 51:43.680
He is my uncle,

51:44.800 --> 51:47.720
so every stitch, stitched with blood.

51:50.720 --> 51:52.960
I heard you dress well, Mr Shelby,

51:56.040 --> 51:57.360
but now I see...

51:58.920 --> 52:00.640
not so well as me.

52:07.720 --> 52:09.640
You know, I have uncles as well...

52:13.480 --> 52:18.200
But they're not the sort of men who
would, who would work in a basement

52:19.000 --> 52:20.640
with a needle and thread,

52:21.800 --> 52:23.040
Mr Changretta.

52:30.720 --> 52:34.680
I am surprised how easy it was
to get into a room with you.

52:37.320 --> 52:39.720
And now?

52:42.080 --> 52:44.160
And now?

52:47.360 --> 52:49.360
And now you should know

52:50.320 --> 52:54.480
that during the trouble you
had earlier on your factory floor

52:54.600 --> 52:58.840
I sent an accomplice
into your office in overalls.

53:02.080 --> 53:03.480
He found your gun...

53:06.080 --> 53:07.520
and unloaded it.

53:15.160 --> 53:16.560
Arthur Shelby.

53:19.120 --> 53:20.000
Polly Gray.

53:23.920 --> 53:25.320
Michael Gray.

53:28.480 --> 53:29.920
John Shelby.

53:37.960 --> 53:39.320
Spent.

53:41.120 --> 53:43.040
Ada Thorne.

53:43.520 --> 53:45.440
And finally...

53:51.920 --> 53:53.480
Tommy Shelby.

53:59.120 --> 54:01.000
None of you will survive.

54:04.240 --> 54:06.880
You're level of security is pitiful

54:09.280 --> 54:14.240
and we are an organisation
of a different dimension.

54:17.680 --> 54:20.520
I could've killed you when
I walked through the door.

54:21.920 --> 54:23.280
But you see...

54:25.680 --> 54:27.520
I want you to be the last.

54:30.480 --> 54:34.800
I want you to be alive after
your entire family is dead

54:35.640 --> 54:38.000
'cause my mother says

54:38.880 --> 54:41.360
that is what will hurt you the most.

54:44.720 --> 54:49.400
You people have
traditions of hon our, as do we.

54:54.480 --> 54:58.520
Instead of sending you a black hand,
I could've had you killed in the night.

54:59.240 --> 55:01.000
I don't know why...

55:07.640 --> 55:10.120
But I want you to know why

55:12.640 --> 55:19.400
and I wanna suggest to you that
we fight this vendetta with hon our.

55:30.480 --> 55:33.480
No civilians, no children.

55:35.440 --> 55:37.040
No police.

55:39.280 --> 55:42.280
Welcome to Birmingham, Mr Changretta.

55:44.240 --> 55:45.760
<i>Grazie.</i>

55:50.680 --> 55:52.920
<i># Where the road is dark</i>

55:54.360 --> 55:58.600
<i># And the seed is sown
Where the gun is cocked... #</i>

55:58.680 --> 56:02.880
Ah, that smell. I miss it.

56:03.000 --> 56:04.560
What, the shit house?

56:06.040 --> 56:10.080
No. I don't know what it is.

56:11.280 --> 56:14.640
Birmingham, I suppose. Small Heath.

56:16.360 --> 56:19.680
-That smell.
-The smell brings it back.

56:21.160 --> 56:22.720
Where's John do you think, Tom?

56:23.960 --> 56:25.440
Fuck knows.

56:26.240 --> 56:28.480
Well, he's gone, though.

56:28.560 --> 56:30.280
Like a hole behind your head.

56:32.640 --> 56:34.720
Thought you thought
there was are heaven.

56:35.240 --> 56:39.000
No. More like hell for our John.

56:40.440 --> 56:41.920
No, neither one.

56:44.160 --> 56:45.920
He's just not here anymore.

56:49.760 --> 56:51.600
<i># Now I been out in the desert</i>

56:53.800 --> 56:56.200
<i># Just doin' my time</i>

56:57.760 --> 57:00.080
<i>#Searchin' through the dust</i>

57:01.560 --> 57:03.640
<i># Lookin' for a sign</i>

57:05.000 --> 57:07.120
<i>#if there's a light up ahead... #</i>

57:07.200 --> 57:10.000
It's like with Grace, Arthur...

57:11.040 --> 57:12.440
They're just gone,

57:13.000 --> 57:14.720
just fucking gone.

57:14.840 --> 57:18.400
<i>#I got this fever burn in'
in my soul #</i>

57:44.320 --> 57:48.880
<i># On a gathering storm comes
a tall handsome man #</i>

57:49.000 --> 57:53.080
